{"ts": "2026-06-07T23:06:13.711032+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "Here are the database migrations in the order they’d be applied (by their numeric prefix). All three are standard PostgreSQL DDL files.\n\n---\n\n### **1. `001_create_users.sql`**  \n**Purpose:** Sets up the foundational `users` table.  \n```sql\nCREATE TABLE users (\n    id           BIGSERIAL PRIMARY KEY,\n    email        TEXT UNIQUE NOT NULL,\n    display_name TEXT,\n    created_at   TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now()\n);\n```\n- `id` – auto‑incrementing 64‑bit integer (BIGSERIAL).  \n- `email` – must be unique and non‑null (likely used for login).  \n- `display_name` – optional human‑friendly name.  \n- `created_at` – timestamp with timezone, automatically set to the current time when a row is inserted.\n\n---\n\n### **2. `002_create_sessions.sql`**  \n**Purpose:** Creates the `sessions` table to track active user sessions (e.g., for web‑app login tokens).  \n```sql\nCREATE TABLE sessions (\n    id          UUID PRIMARY KEY,\n    user_id     BIGINT NOT NULL REFERENCES users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n    issued_at   TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now(),\n    expires_at  TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL\n);\n```\n- `id` – UUID (v4) as the session identifier (common for stateless tokens).  \n- `user_id` – foreign key linking to `users.id`; if a user is deleted, their sessions are automatically removed (`ON DELETE CASCADE`).  \n- `issued_at` – when the session was created (defaults to now).  \n- `expires_at` – when the session becomes invalid (no default, must be supplied by the application).\n\n---\n\n### **3. `003_add_session_index.sql`**  \n**Purpose:** Adds an index to speed up lookups on `sessions.user_id`.  \n```sql\nCREATE INDEX idx_sessions_user_id ON sessions(user_id);\n```\n- This is a performance optimization: queries that join or filter sessions by user (e.g., “get all active sessions for user X”) will be much faster.\n\n---\n\n### **Typical application order**\n1. Run `001_create_users.sql` – the `users` table must exist before any session rows can reference it.  \n2. Run `002_create_sessions.sql` – creates the `sessions` table with the foreign‑key constraint.  \n3. Run `003_add_session_index.sql` – adds the index after the table is populated (or concurrently, depending on your migration tool).\n\nMost migration frameworks (Flyway, Liquibase, Django, Rails, Alembic, etc.) would execute these files in the order of their numeric prefixes. If you’re using a custom script, you’d typically sort the filenames lexicographically (`001_…`, `002_…`, `003_…`).\n\n---\n\nThat’s the complete migration set currently in the repository. Let me know if you’d like to explore the `seeds`, `scripts`, or `config` directories next!", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 1030, "prompt_tokens": 5924, "total_tokens": 6954, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": 0, "reasoning_tokens": 376, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null, "image_tokens": 0}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": 0, "cached_tokens": 5440, "cache_write_tokens": 0, "video_tokens": 0}, "cost": 0, "is_byok": true, "cost_details": {"upstream_inference_cost": 0.000371392, "upstream_inference_prompt_cost": 8.2992e-05, "upstream_inference_completions_cost": 0.0002884}}, "model_provider": "openai", "model_name": "xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-20260422", "system_fingerprint": null, "id": "gen-1780873560-1lC70km2Qee9l0XJs8oL", "finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "type": "ai", "name": null, "id": "lc_run--019ea456-0173-7610-aad0-6f233dedd9b7-0", "tool_calls": [], "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 5924, "output_tokens": 1030, "total_tokens": 6954, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 5440}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 376}}}}]}}}
